\f1\fs27\cf1\ltrpar\ql\sb450\sa45\li150\ri45 Q5.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 A company operates a cinema which has three different screens. Each screen has a capacity determined by the number of seats the screen has.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Each seat is identified by a unique seat number for the screen it is in, but two seats in different screens can have the same number. A specific seat is classified as being of one of two types: standard or deluxe.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 On a particular day, there will be several showings of films in each of the screens. A screen might show the same film multiple times or it might show different films at different times of day.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Customers make bookings to go to the cinema. Each booking is for one specific showing of a film. A booking is for one or more seats, and the customer can select the individual seats that they want to book when they make the booking.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 When a booking is made, if the customer has not previously made a booking, the customer\u8217?s first name, last name and telephone number are recorded. If the booking is for more than one seat then only the details of the person who made the booking are recorded \u8211? the system does not store the details of who will be sitting in each seat. If a customer has made a booking previously then the details that were stored about them when the previous booking was made are re-used.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 (a)\u8195?\~Develop a \b fully normalised design\b0  for a relational database to store the information required by the cinema. To help you, the Screen, Seat, Film and Showing relations have already been defined in \b Figure 1\b0 .\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\fi0 Figure 1\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1701\ri567 Screen(\ul ScreenNumber\ul0 , Capacity)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1701\ri567 Seat(\ul SeatNumber, ScreenNumber\ul0 , SeatType)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1701\ri567 Film(\ul FilmID\ul0 , FilmName, Duration, Certificate)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1701\ri567 Showing(\ul ShowingID\ul0 , ScreenNumber, FilmID, ShowTime, ShowDate)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb360\sa0\li1134\ri567 Using the format shown in \b Figure 1\b0  list the other \b three\b0  relations that will need to be created, together with the attributes that each relation will contain.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 Underline the attribute(s) that will form the entity identifier (primary key) in each relation.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
