\f1\fs20\cf0\b\ltrpar\qr\sb60\sa0\li0\ri0 (1)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 (f)\u8195?\u8194?JSON is used to encode datasets when they are passed between the server and the booking application. \b Figure 3\b0  shows an example of how data about some films can be encoded using JSON.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\fi0 Figure 3\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li2268\ri567 \{"Films":[\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\{ "FilmID": 4301,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"FilmName": "Alien Doomsday",\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"Duration": 106,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"Certificate": "12A" \},\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\{ "FilmID": 2098,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"FilmName": "Tom's Amazing Adventure",\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"Duration": 84,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?"Certificate": "U" \}\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 ]\}\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 State \b two\b0  reasons why JSON might have been chosen to encode the data instead of XML, assuming that the software supports both methods.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 Reason 1\~\~__________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 Reason 2\~\~__________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 ___________________________________________________________________\par
\f1\fs20\cf0\b\ltrpar\qr\sb60\sa0\li0\ri0 (2)\par
\f1\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\qr\sb60\sa0 (Total 13 marks)\par
\f1\fs27\cf1\ltrpar\ql\sb450\sa45\li150\ri45 Q6.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 A network of zoos uses a relational database system to store information about the animals that they have so that they can be matched up with animals at other zoos in a breeding programme.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Figure 1\b0  shows the structure of the relations in the database.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0 Figure 1\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1701\ri567 Zoo(\ul ZooName\ul0 , Town, Country)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1701\ri567 AnimalLocation(\ul AnimalID\ul0 , \ul ZooName\ul0 , \ul DateArrived\ul0 , DateLeft)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1701\ri567 Animal(\ul AnimalID\ul0 , IndividualName, Species, DateOfBirth, Sex)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1701\ri567 Match(\ul AnimalFemaleID\ul0 , \ul AnimalMaleID\ul0 , \ul DateOfMatch\ul0 , Successful)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~The Zoo relation stores details of the zoos that participate in the breeding programme. Each zoo is uniquely identified by its ZooName.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~The AnimalLocation relation identifies which zoos each animal has lived at. The zoo that the animal is currently at can be identified because the DateLeft attribute is set to 01/01/0001 to indicate that the animal has not left.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~The Animal relation stores details of the individual animals that are available to be matched with other animals for breeding. Each animal is identified by a unique number, the AnimalID. The individual name of the animal (eg \u8216?Timothy\u8217?) is also stored, together with the species of the animal (eg \u8216?Red Panda\u8217?), its date of birth and its sex (\u8216?Male\u8217? or \u8216?Female\u8217?).\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~The Match relation stores details of matches that have been made. The attributes AnimalFemaleID and AnimalMaleID refer to the AnimalID values of the two matched animals in the Animal relation.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 (a)\u8195?\~Shade \b one\b0  lozenge to identify which of the properties below \b does not have to be true\b0  for a fully normalised database.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li0\ri0\fi0 \~\par

