\f1\fs27\cf1\ltrpar\ql\sb450\sa45\li150\ri45 Q12.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 Employees at a bank use client computers to access data that is stored on a database server.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 The database server uses software to query and modify data stored in a database on hard disk drives. It returns the results of these queries to the clients over the bank\u8217?s computer network.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 The performance of the system is unsatisfactory: the time-delay between a client sending a query to the server and the client receiving the results is unacceptably long.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 Explain how the performance of the system might be improved. You should consider the following factors that might be affecting the performance:\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~the hardware of the server\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~the design of the computer network\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~the database and software running on the server.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567\fi0 In your answer you will be assessed on your ability to follow a line of reasoning to produce a coherent, relevant and structured response.\par
\f1\fs20\cf0\b\ltrpar\qr\sb60\sa0\li0\ri0 (Total 12 marks)\par
\f1\fs27\cf1\ltrpar\ql\sb450\sa45\li150\ri45 Q13.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li567\ri567 Athletes, who are members of teams, compete in running events, which are held at fixtures throughout the year.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 For example, athlete 15 might compete in the Girls\u8217? 1500m Under 18 race in the fixture at Marsten on 12 September 2018.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li567\ri567 A relational database is used to store the details of which athletes enter each event at each fixture. The relations used in the database are shown in \b Figure 1\b0 .\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0 Figure 1\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 Athlete(\ul AthleteID\ul0 , Surname, Forename, DateOfBirth, Gender, TeamName)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567 EventType(\ul EventTypeID\ul0 , Gender, Distance, AgeGroup)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567 Fixture(\ul FixtureID\ul0 , FixtureDate, LocationName)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567 EventAtFixture(\ul FixtureID, EventTypeID\ul0 )\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb90\sa0\li1134\ri567 EventEntry(\ul FixtureID, EventTypeID, AthleteID\ul0 )\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~Each Athlete, EventType and Fixture is identified by a unique identity number, for example AthleteID for athletes.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~An EventType is a type of event, such as Boys\u8217? 100m Under 15 race.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 \u8226?\u8195?\u8195?\~If an athlete wants to take part in an event at a particular fixture, then an entry is created in the EventEntry relation to represent this.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 (a)\u8195?\~\b Figure 2\b0  shows an incomplete entity-relationship diagram for part of the database.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi0 Draw lines on \b Figure 2\b0  to show the degree of any \b three\b0  relationships that exist between the four entities shown.\par
\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0{\pict\jpegblip\picw6675\pich3060\picwgoal6675\pichgoal3060\picscalex100\picscaley100
}\~\par
\f1\fs20\cf0\b\ltrpar\qr\sb60\sa0 (2)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567\fi-567 (b)\u8195?\~\b Figure 3\b0  shows an SQL statement that is intended to make a table to represent the Athlete relation. The statement contains some errors.\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\b\ltrpar\qc\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\fi0 Figure 3\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\b0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?CREATE TABLE Athlete (\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~PRIMARY KEY AthleteID,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~VARCHAR(50) Surname,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~VARCHAR(30) Forename,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~DATE DateOfBirth,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~VARCHAR(6) Gender,\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\~\~\~VARCHAR(30) TeamName\par
\f2\fs20\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb0\sa0\li2268\ri567 \u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?\u8195?)\par
\f1\fs22\cf0\ltrpar\ql\sb240\sa0\li1134\ri567 You may assume that all of the data types used in \b Figure 3\b0  are valid and the field lengths are appropriate.\par
